{"title_page": "Andrey Vdovin", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Andrey Vdovin\n| nickname = \n| headercolor= yellow\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Russia]]n\n| sport = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n| event = [[Sprint (athletics)|Sprint]]<br/>[[middle-distance running|Middle distance]]\n|disability = \n|disability_class = [[T37 (classification)|T37]]\n| club = \n| coach = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1994|2|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{RUS}} \n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|0|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|6|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|5|1|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{RUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metres relay|4x100m - T35-38]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T38]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T38]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T38]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrey Vdovin''' ({{lang-ru|'''\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0412\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d'''}}, also [[transliterated]] '''Andrei Vdovin''', born 26 February 1994) is a [[Russia]]n parasport [[Track and field|athlete]] competing mainly in category [[T37 (classification)|T37]] [[Sprint (running)|sprint]] and [[middle-distance running|middle-distance]] events. A triple gold medal winner at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]], Vdovin also set three world records in his class between 2013 and 2014.\n\n==Personal history==\nVdovin was born in [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia]] in 1994.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/swansea-2014/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_EC2014AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=19512.htm|title=Vdovin, Andrey: Biography overview|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=paralympic.org}}</ref> He has [[cerebral palsy]].<ref name=\"IPC\">{{cite web |url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=1187789&refreshauto=1|title=Vdovin, Andrey|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref> After leaving secondary education he enrolled at the [[Nizhny Novgorod State Technical University]] to study Information Technology.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Athletics career==\nVdovin took up athletics at the age of 10 and later joined the Specialised Children's Youth Sport School of Olympic Reserve in [[Zarya]].<ref name=\"IPC\"/><ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/andrey-vdovin|title=Andrey Vdovin|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=paralympic.org}}</ref> He was classified as a T37 athlete, due to limited motor function resulting from his cerebral palsy. In 2013 he was selected to represent Russia at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]] in Lyon. There he entered three events, the 100m, 200m and the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metres relay|4 \u00d7 100 m - T35-38]]. He won gold in all three and set a world record in both the 100m (11.48) and the 200m (22.77).<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/> His winning time in the 200m saw him become the first man to run under 23 seconds in his classification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/new-star-sophie-hahn-shines-with-world-record|title=New star Sophie Hahn shines with World record at IPC Athletics World Championships |date=25 July 2015|work=iaaf.org|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> In the T35-38 100m relay, he was joined by [[Gocha Khugaev]], [[Roman Kapranov]] and [[Evgenii Shvetcov]], beating South Africa (silver) and Ukraine (bronze) in the final.\n\nThe following year he represented Russia at Nottwil in Switzerland in an open meet. There he entered the 400m middle-distance event where his time of 51.67 not only gave him the gold medal, but also set a new world record.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/> Three months later he was back in the Russian team at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Swansea. He entered the 100m and 200m sprint events along with and the 400m. Vdovin won both the sprint events and broke his own world record in the 400m with a time of 50.91 seconds.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=andrei-vdovin|old_id=1187789|name=Andrei Vdovin}} ([https://web.archive.org/web/20160304032650/http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&gender=all&name=Vdovin&fname=Andrey archive])\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vdovin, Andrey}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Russian male sprinters]]\n[[Category:Russian male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes with cerebral palsy]]\n[[Category:World Para Athletics Championships winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian Paralympic athlete}}\n{{Infobox athlete\n| name = Andrey Vdovin\n| nickname = \n| headercolor= yellow\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Russia]]n\n| sport = [[Paralympic athletics]]\n| event = [[Sprint (athletics)|Sprint]]<br/>[[middle-distance running|Middle distance]]\n|disability = \n|disability_class = [[T37 (classification)|T37]]\n| club = \n| coach = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1994|2|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{RUS}} \n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|0|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|World Championships]]|6|0|0\n|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|European Championships]]|5|1|0\n}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Paralympic athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{RUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|2013 Lyon]]|[[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metres relay|4x100m - T35-38]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships|2015 Doha]]|[[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IPC Athletics European Championships|IPC European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships|2014 Swansea]]|[[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T37]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metres|100m - T38]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 400 metres|400m - T38]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships|2016 Grosseto]]|[[2016 IPC Athletics European Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metres|200m - T38]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrey Vdovin''' (Russian: \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0412\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d) (26 February 1994) is a [[Russia]]n parasport [[Track and field|athlete]] competing mainly in category [[T37 (classification)|T37]] [[Sprint (running)|sprint]] and [[middle-distance running|middle-distance]] events. A triple gold medal winner at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships]], Vdovin also set three world records in his class between 2013 and 2014.\n\n==Personal history==\nAndrey Vdovin was born in [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia]] in 1994.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/static/info/swansea-2014/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_EC2014AT@@@@@@@ENG_number=19512.htm|title=Vdovin, Andrey: Biography overview|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=paralympic.org}}</ref> He has [[cerebral palsy]].<ref name=\"IPC\">{{cite web |url=http://ipc.infostradasports.com/asp/lib/theasp.asp?pageid=8937&sportid=513&personid=1187789&refreshauto=1|title=Vdovin, Andrey|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[International Paralympic Committee|IPC]]}}</ref> After leaving secondary education he enrolled at the [[Nizhny Novgorod State Technical University]] to study Information Technology.<ref name=\"IPC\"/>\n\n==Athletics career==\nVdovin took up athletics at the age of 10 and later joined the Specialised Children's Youth Sport School of Olympic Reserve in [[Zarya]].<ref name=\"IPC\"/><ref name=\"IPC Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/andrey-vdovin|title=Andrey Vdovin|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=paralympic.org}}</ref> He was classified as a T37 athlete, due to limited motor function resulting from his cerebral palsy. In 2013 he was selected to represent Russia at the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships|IPC World Championships]] in Lyon. There he entered three events, the 100m, 200m and the [[2013 IPC Athletics World Championships \u2013 Men's 4 x 100 metres relay|4 \u00d7 100 m - T35-38]]. He won gold in all three and set a world record in both the 100m (11.48) and the 200m (22.77).<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/> His winning time in the 200m saw him become the first man to run under 23 seconds in his classification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/new-star-sophie-hahn-shines-with-world-record|title=New star Sophie Hahn shines with World record at IPC Athletics World Championships |date=25 July 2015|work=iaaf.org|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> In the T35-38 100m relay, he was joined by [[Gocha Khugaev]], [[Roman Kapranov]] and [[Evgenii Shvetcov]], beating South Africa (silver) and Ukraine (bronze) in the final.\n\nThe following year he represented Russia at Nottwil in Switzerland in an open meet. There he entered the 400m middle-distance event where his time of 51.67 not only gave him the gold medal, but also set a new world record.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/> Three months later he was back in the Russian team at the [[2014 IPC Athletics European Championships]] in Swansea. He entered the 100m and 200m sprint events along with and the 400m. Vdovin won both the sprint events and broke his own world record in the 400m with a time of 50.91 seconds.<ref name=\"paralympic.org\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304032650/http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/search.php?sport=all&games=all&medal=all&npc=all&gender=all&name=Vdovin&fname=Andrey Andrey Vdovin at the International Paralympic Committee]\n* {{IPC athlete|1187789}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vdovin, Andrey}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:World record holders in Paralympic athletics]]\n[[Category:Russian male sprinters]]\n[[Category:Russian male middle-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes with cerebral palsy]]\n[[Category:World Para Athletics Championships winners]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrey_Vdovin"}
